# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mes-manufacturing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mes-manufacturing/isa-95] There are 5 parts of the ISA-95 standard.
[src:mes-manufacturing/isa-95] The models help define boundaries between the enterprise systems and the control systems.
[src:mes-manufacturing/isa-95] They help address questions like which tasks can be executed by which function and what information must be exchanged between applications.
[src:mes-manufacturing/isa-95] Here is a Archived 2014-11-05 at the Wayback Machine.
[src:mes-manufacturing/isa-95] Within production areas activities are executed and information is passed back and forth.
[src:mes-manufacturing/isa-95] The standard provides reference models for production activities, quality activities, maintenance activities and inventory activities.
[src:mes-manufacturing/manufacturing-execution-system] MES creates the "as-built" record, capturing the data, processes and outcomes of the manufacturing process.
[src:mes-manufacturing/manufacturing-execution-system] This can be especially important in regulated industries, such as food and beverage or pharmaceutical, where documentation and proof of processes, events and actions may be required.
[src:mes-manufacturing/manufacturing-execution-system] As of 2025, the manufacturing execution systems are shifting from rigid, monolithic on-premise software to modular, cloud-connected platforms.
[src:mes-manufacturing/manufacturing-execution-system] "Manufacturing execution systems [help] create flawless manufacturing processes and provide real-time feedback of requirement changes", and provide information at a single source.
[src:mes-manufacturing/manufacturing-execution-system] A wide variety of systems arose using collected data for a dedicated purpose.
[src:mes-manufacturing/manufacturing-execution-system] Further development of these systems during the 1990s introduced overlap in functionality.
[src:mes-manufacturing/manufacturing-execution-system] Then the Manufacturing Enterprise Solutions Association International (MESA) introduced some structure by defining 11 functions that set the scope of MES.
[src:mes-manufacturing/manufacturing-execution-system] In 2000, the ANSI/ISA-95 standard merged this model with the Purdue Reference Model (PRM).
[src:mes-manufacturing/manufacturing-execution-system] A functional hierarchy was defined in which MES were situated at Level 3 between ERP at Level 4 and process control at Levels 0, 1, 2.
[src:mes-manufacturing/manufacturing-execution-system] With the publication of the third part of the standard in 2005, activities in Level 3 were divided over four main operations: production, quality, logistics and maintenance.
[src:mes-manufacturing/manufacturing-execution-system] Between 2005 and 2013, additional or revised parts of the ANSI/ISA-95 standard defined the architecture of an MES into more detail, covering how to internally distribute functionality and what information to exchange internally as well as externally.
[src:mes-manufacturing/manufacturing-execution-system] Over the years, international standards and models have refined the scope of such systems in terms of activities.
[src:mes-manufacturing/manufacturing-execution-system] MES integrates with ISA-95 (previous Purdue Reference Model, “95”) with multiple relationships.
[src:mes-manufacturing/manufacturing-execution-system] The collection of systems acting on the ISA-95 Level 3 can be called manufacturing operations management systems (MOMS).
[src:mes-manufacturing/manufacturing-execution-system] Apart from an MES, there are typically laboratory information management system (LIMS), warehouse management system (WMS) and computerized maintenance management system (CMMS).
[src:mes-manufacturing/manufacturing-execution-system] Examples of systems acting on ISA-95 Level 4 are product lifecycle management (PLM), enterprise resource planning (ERP), customer relationship management (CRM), human resource management (HRM), and process development execution system (PDES).
[src:mes-manufacturing/manufacturing-execution-system] In many cases, middleware enterprise application integration (EAI) systems are being used to exchange transaction messages between MES and Level 4 systems.
[src:mes-manufacturing/manufacturing-execution-system] A common data definition, B2MML, has been defined within the ISA-95 standard to link MES systems to these Level 4 systems.
[src:mes-manufacturing/manufacturing-execution-system] Systems acting on ISA-95 Level 2 are supervisory control and data acquisition (SCADA), programmable logic controllers (PLC), distributed control systems (DCS) and building automation systems (BAS).
[src:mes-manufacturing/manufacturing-execution-system] Most MES systems include connectivity as part of their product offering.
[src:mes-manufacturing/manufacturing-execution-system] Direct communication of plant floor equipment data is established by connecting to the PLC.
[src:mes-manufacturing/manufacturing-execution-system] Often, plant floor data is first collected and diagnosed for real-time control in a DCS or SCADA system.
[src:mes-manufacturing/manufacturing-execution-system] In this case, the MES systems connect to these Level 2 systems for exchanging plant floor data.
[src:mes-manufacturing/manufacturing-execution-system] The industry standard for plant floor connectivity has evolved from OLE for Process Control (OPC) to OPC Unified Architecture (OPC-UA).
[src:mes-manufacturing/manufacturing-execution-system] Unlike its predecessor, OPC-UA is platform-independent, allowing it to run on Linux and embedded devices while offering robust security models.
[src:mes-manufacturing/manufacturing-execution-system] In modern Industry 4.0 architectures, MES connectivity often extends beyond the traditional hierarchy.
[src:mes-manufacturing/manufacturing-execution-system] Systems increasingly utilize IIoT protocols like MQTT (often with Sparkplug B) to transmit lightweight data to cloud-based analytics platforms, creating a hybrid architecture where OPC-UA handles complex machine data and MQTT handles rapid telemetry.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Measuring OEE is a manufacturing best practice.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] By measuring OEE and the underlying losses, important insights can be gained on how to systematically improve the manufacturing process.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Technically, OEE is an effective metric for identifying and visualizing losses, and steering the improvement of the effectiveness of manufacturing equipment by eliminating 'waste'.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Socially, OEE can provide a common language for groups speaking in different 'languages' such as shop floor (units), managers (money) or planners (time).
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The term OEE was first mentioned in Seiichi Nakajima's book 'TPM Tenkai' in 1982.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] OEE was described as a central part of the Total Productive Maintenance methodology.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] It is based on the Harrington Emerson way of thinking regarding labor efficiency.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] 100% OEE is considered to be a theoretical reference point where a machine would be permanently running, at its theoretical maximal speed, producing only good products.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Anything hindering this is considered to be a 'loss'.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] When running: Is the machine running at theoretical maximal speed?
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Is the output meeting its specifications?
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The first question leads to the 'availabilty rate' of the equipment, the second one to the 'performance rate' and the third one to the 'quality rate'.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] in this way, a cascade of effectiveness and effectiveness losses arises.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The quality rate refers to a part of the performance (the part that there was 'speed', the other part is lost in the performance rate).
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The Performance rate refers to part of the availability (the time there was output - the other part is lost in the availability rate).
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Each of the three components of the OEE points to an aspect of the process that can be targeted for improvement.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] OEE may be applied to any individual equipment or line.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This tool also allows for drilling down for very specific analysis, such as a particular Time frame, Shift, Team or any of several other parameters.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Although the performance of a particular product can be determined from OEE data, OEE cannot be calculated for that product because this would require that all downtime (availability losses) should be correlated to specific products.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] OEE focusses on the 'if not' in the equations: Where did potential effectiveness got lost?
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] These 'losses' of effectiveness are being subdivided further into what is known as the 'Six Big Losses' to OEE.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] In order to make this more universally applicable and also to better reflect the financial impact of the losses, the original six big losses were later adjusted slightly.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The reason for identifying the losses in these categories is so that specific countermeasures can be applied to reduce the loss and improve the overall OEE.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Multiplying the three underlying grades AxPxQ results in a percentage value that indicates the proportion of the scheduled machine running time during which production actually met the quality criteria.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This value is always well below 100%, as 100% is a theoretical value.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Even if a system runs continuously at maximum speed without causing a single defect, it will for example still need to be serviced at some point.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Alternatively, the OEE as a number could be calculated by dividing the minimum time needed to produce the parts under optimal conditions by the actual time needed to produce the parts.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] However, in this way the losses are no longer known, meaning the most important part of OEE is missing.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The value range for OEE is between 0% and 100%.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] If an effectiveness level of more than 100% is displayed, this indicates an error in the definition.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The Availability portion of the OEE Metric represents the percentage of scheduled time (also referred to as 'loading time') that the equipment is available to operate.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] A given machine is scheduled to run for an 8-hour (480-minute) shift with a 30-minute break, during which the machine is being stopped, and there is a breakdown of 60 minutes.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] During the scheduled operating time of 480 minutes, the machine was waiting 30 min. because of the break and 60 minutes because it broke down.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The performance rate represents the ratio between the theoretical maximum speed of the machine and its actual speed.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Performance can only be calculated when there is output; thus during actual running time.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] While the actual performance can be measured, it is often difficult in operational practice to obtain the theoretical maximum speed as a reference value.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The technical data provided by the machine manufacturer does not usually correspond to the theoretically possible maximum values, e.g. to avoid complaints or for other reasons.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Defining a too low maximum speed will become visible when the performance goes above 100%, which is undesirable.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Ultimately, the goal of OEE is to reveal all potential.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] It is a good practice to calculate the maximum value based on physical limits, e.g., a calculation of heat transfer, the power of a motor, or the fall speed of a product.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] If that fails, the concept of "best demonstrated cycle time" has proven itself.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This involves determining the production speeds of products from the past and increasing the highest production speed by a margin of 20%.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Defining this as 100% performance may lead to a structurally too low OEE, however it will visualize any potential loss on the performance.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The factor 1 (100%) now represents a peak value that is never exceeded, even for a short time.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] For systems that only manufacture one or a few products, calculating the performance factor is simple.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] If a large number of different products with different maximum speeds are run on one system (multi-product companies), the effort required to determine the maximum speed can be high and the performance should be calculated correctly using a weighted average.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] A given equipment is scheduled to run for an 8-hour (480-minute) and has 90 min downtime.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The equipment produces 242 Total Units during the shift.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Note: The basis is Total Units, not Good Units.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The Performance metric does not penalize for Quality.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The Quality portion of the OEE Metric represents the Good Units produced as a percentage of the Total Units produced.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The Quality Metric is a pure measurement of Process Yield that is designed to exclude the effects of Availability and Performance.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The losses due to defects and rework are called *quality losses*.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The calculations of OEE may not seem to be particularly complicated, but care must be taken as to standards that are used as the basis.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] In order to visualize all losses, it is crucial to use the right 'configuration' of the metric.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Definitions — for parts — of the OEE can be found in ISO 22400-2:2014. and VDI 3423:2011-08 (2011) These definitions are not standardized for all industries and are individually tailored to the respective company in its application.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Furthermore, the ISO 22400 standard presents two different OEE versions that appear to be inconsistent with one another, the first of which – in the standard's normative section – contains no reference to or connection with the original Nakajima's Total Productive Maintenance (TPM) model.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] To resolve this ambiguity, academic literature provides a comprehensive classification framework that maps the standard's time elements to the traditional OEE formula, ensuring consistency between the ISO standard and established industrial practices.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This to OEE dedicated standard aims for the visualisation of all effectiveness losses on any manufacturing equipment, being unabigiously clear to production personnel.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The standard uses the same logic and uniform terminology for any type of equipment.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] In order to calculate OEE, operational data needs to be acquired from the production process.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This needs to reflect 'what happened' on one hand, and 'what did not happen' (the losses) on the other hand.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Depending on the systems or products, it can be difficult to collect the basic data required to determine the key figure.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Many companies therefore rely on special software for data collection.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The goal of TPM (Total Productive Maintenance) as set out by Seiichi Nakajima, is "The continuous improvement of OEE by engaging all those that impact on it in small group activities".
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] To achieve this, the TPM toolbox sets out a Focused improvement tactic to reduce each of the six types of OEE loss.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] For example, the Focused improvement tactic to systematically reduce breakdown risk sets out how to improve asset condition and standardise working methods to reduce human error and accelerated wear.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Zero Failure Management provides a profound structure to achieve this.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Combining OEE with Focused improvement converts OEE from a lagging to a leading indicator that can be used to guide performance management priorities.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The first Focused improvement stage of OEE improvement is to achieve a stable OEE, i.e. one which varies at around 5% from the mean for a representative production sample.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This indicates that the asset performance is stable and not affected by variability in equipment wear rates and working methods.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The second stage of OEE improvement (optimisation) is meant to remove chronic losses.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] As the TPM process delivers these gains through small cross functional improvement teams, the process of OEE improvement should also raise front line team engagement, problem ownership, collaboration and skill levels.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This combination of OEE as a KPI, TPM Focused improvement tactics and front line team engagement is intended to make the gains sustainable and deliver the TPM goal of year on year improvement in OEE.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Zero Failure Management helps significantly to achieve this.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] OEE measurement is also commonly used as a key performance indicator (KPI) in conjunction with lean manufacturing efforts.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] To achieve the main goal of Lean, creating flow, individual pieces of equipment need to be fully reliable and in tune.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] TEEP, therefore, reports the 'bottom line' effectiveness of manufacturing equipment.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] To calculate the Total Effective Equipment Performance(TEEP), the OEE is multiplied by a fourth component: Loading.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The Loading rate of the TEEP Metric represents the percentage of time that the equipment is scheduled to operate compared to the total Calendar Time that is available.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The Loading Metric is a pure measurement of Schedule effectiveness and is designed to exclude the effects how well that equipment may perform.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] A given equipment is scheduled to run 5 Days per Week, 24 Hours per Day.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] For a given week, the Total Calendar Time is 7 Days at 24 Hours.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The advantage of OEE lies in the transparency of the value added share and the associated losses of the equipment.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The term "Overall Equipment Efficiency" is often wrongly used as a synonym for "Overall Equipment Effectiveness".
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Measures that increase production output but incur disproportionately high costs may well be effective, but at the same time they may be inefficient and therefore economically unviable and thus unproductive.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Often, insufficient quality is not detected at the equipment that caused it.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] In this case, it has proven effective to apply the "discovery principle," i.e., to apply an OEE reduction to the equipment where the error was discovered.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This removes the OEE from being purely equipment-related and turns it into a process indicator.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] However, the OEE of a piece of equipment can of course also be optimized by making improvements to other equipment.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The OEE should also be a key figure that is as up-to-date as possible.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] In this respect, the OK quantity should be determined at the latest at the end of the shift and the OEE calculated.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] From the perspective of Process Control, the question rises how an operator can be responsible for manufacturing correct products if he cannot see whether the products are correct.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] To highlight this problem, it is worth considering blocked products as a quality issue: after all, they were not right the first time around.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Valuable activities such as setup or maintenance will also reduce overall equipment effectiveness (OEE) at the beginning.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] If setup activities reduce overall equipment effectiveness, there is an incentive to reduce setup times using SMED (Single-minute exchange of die).
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] On the other hand, this also means that OEE can be increased by reducing the number of changeovers, i.e. by increasing batch sizes.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This would contradict the principles of lean production.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This highlights the importance of a clear explanation of OEE: the goal is not to be as high as possible, but to identify obstacles and then eliminate them.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] A convention must be agreed within the company to define when downtime occurs.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Recording and justifying every second of equipment downtime is too time-consuming for most companies.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] In practice, a recording limit of 1 to 5 minutes of equipment downtime has proven to be a pragmatic approach.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] All downtimes of less than one minute are therefore included in the performance rate.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The collected data must be processed in order to obtain meaningful information.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This information is aimed at various target groups, such as.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Meaningful analyses prove to be the key to good decisions.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Theoretically, this is only possible with very precise figures.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] In practice, it has been shown that correctly selected data has a greater effect in this respect than high precision.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Although tempting, OEE (as a number) is NOT suitable for comparing machines or benchmarking.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] For similar reasons, OEE may not be applied to aggregate to Department or Plant levels.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Where multiple machines are linked together, each individual piece of equipment will display the waiting categories "No Input" (Starved) and "No output" (Blocked) in addition to the standard standstill reasons.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This allows upstream or downstream faults in production equipment to be identified.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The use of OEE requires knowledge of manufacturing environments and understanding of the underlying data.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Without this, a specific OEE number may be of little to no value.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] OEE cannot be used to measure employee performance.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] It is used to identify and measure equipment losses, which can then be eliminated through appropriate root cause analysis and measures.
[src:mes-manufacturing/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Using OEE as a heuristic is not recommended.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs can range from small modular devices with tens of inputs and outputs (I/O), in a housing integral with the processor, to large rack-mounted modular devices with thousands of I/O, and which are often networked to other PLC and SCADA systems.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] They can be designed for many arrangements of digital and analog I/O, extended temperature ranges, immunity to electrical noise, and resistance to vibration and impact.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs were first developed in the automobile manufacturing industry to provide flexible, rugged and easily programmable controllers to replace hard-wired relay logic systems.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Dick Morley, who invented the first PLC, the Modicon 084, for General Motors in 1968, is considered the father of PLC.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] A PLC is an example of a hard real-time system since output results must be produced in response to input conditions within a limited time, otherwise unintended operation may result.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Programs to control machine operation are typically stored in battery-backed-up or non-volatile memory.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] The PLC originated in the late 1960s in the automotive industry in the US and was designed to replace relay logic systems.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Before, control logic for manufacturing was mainly composed of relays, cam timers, drum sequencers, and dedicated closed-loop controllers.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] The hard-wired nature of these components made it difficult for design engineers to alter the automation process.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Changes would require rewiring and careful updating of the documentation.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] When general-purpose computers became available, they were soon applied to control logic in industrial processes.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] These early computers were unreliable and required specialist programmers and strict control of working conditions, such as temperature, cleanliness, and power quality.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] The PLC provided several advantages over earlier automation systems.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] It was designed to tolerate the industrial environment better than systems intended for office use, and was more reliable, compact, and required less maintenance than relay systems.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] It was easily expandable with additional I/O modules.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] While relay systems required tedious and sometimes complicated hardware changes in case of reconfiguration, a PLC can be reconfigured by loading new or modified code.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] This allowed for easier iteration over manufacturing process design.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] With a simple programming language focused on logic and switching operations, it was more user-friendly than computers using general-purpose programming languages.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Early PLCs were programmed in ladder logic, which strongly resembled a schematic diagram of relay logic.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] It also permitted its operation to be monitored.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] In recent years, the introduction of virtual PLCs has expanded the scope of programmable logic controllers.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Virtual PLCs are software-based controllers that simulate the functions of traditional PLCs but are executed on general-purpose hardware, offering a more cost-effective and flexible alternative.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] These controllers enable automation systems to be managed without the need for dedicated hardware, making them ideal for applications requiring simulation, remote control, or cloud-based systems.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] In 1968, GM Hydramatic, the automatic transmission division of General Motors, issued a request for proposals for an electronic replacement for hard-wired relay systems based on a white paper written by engineer Edward R.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] The winning proposal came from Bedford Associates from Bedford, Massachusetts.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] The result, built in 1969, was the first PLC and designated the *084*, because it was Bedford Associates' eighty-fourth project.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Bedford Associates started a company, **Modicon, Inc.**, dedicated to developing, manufacturing, selling, and servicing this new product, which they named **Modicon** (standing for "modular digital controller").
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] One of the people who worked on that project was Dick Morley, who is considered to be the father of the PLC.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] The Modicon brand was sold in 1977 to Gould Electronics and later to Schneider Electric, its current owner.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] About this same time, Modicon created Modbus, a data communications protocol to be used with its PLCs.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Modbus has since become a standard open protocol commonly used to connect many industrial electrical devices.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] One of the first Modicon 084 models built is now on display at Schneider Electric's facility in North Andover, Massachusetts.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] It was presented to Modicon by GM, when the unit was retired after nearly twenty years of uninterrupted service.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Modicon used the 84 moniker at the end of its product range like Modicon Micro 84 and Modicon TSX CSY 84 until after the 984 made its appearance.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] In a parallel development, Odo Josef Struger is sometimes known as the "father of the programmable logic controller" as well.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] He was involved in the invention of the Allen-Bradley programmable logic controller.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Prior to the release of the IBM "Personal Computer" in 1981, these devices were commonly known simply as "Programmable Controllers", or "PC's.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] But rapid expansion of the personal computer industry in the early 1980's, the abbreviation "PC" was rapidly and universally accepted as a reference to "Personal Computers".
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Odo was later credited with coining the "PLC" acronym to distinguish these two technologies, And the inclusion of the word "Logic" was an easy choice as "Ladder Logic" had already been accepted as the name of the programming language.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Allen-Bradley (now a brand owned by Rockwell Automation) went on to become the dominant PLC manufacturer in the United States during his tenure.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Struger played a leadership role in developing IEC 61131-3 PLC programming language standards.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Allen-Bradley's PLC-5 family, preceded by the 1774-PLC (released in the 1980's, was the first modular design found in modern-day systems.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] While Modicon was the most popular of the first full featured PLC's through the early 1980's, Allen Bradley overtook them in the mid-1980's and grew to own the largest market share of PLC hardware and software in North America.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Many early PLC programming applications were not capable of graphical representation of the logic, and so it was instead represented as a series of logic expressions in some kind of Boolean format, similar to Boolean algebra.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] As programming terminals evolved, because ladder logic was a familiar format used for electro-mechanical control panels, it became more commonly used.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Newer formats, such as state logic, function block diagrams, and structured text exist.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Ladder logic remains popular because PLCs solve the logic in a predictable and repeating sequence, and ladder logic allows the person writing the logic to see any issues with the timing of the logic sequence more easily than would be possible in other formats.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Up to the mid-1990s, PLCs were programmed using proprietary programming panels or special-purpose programming terminals, which often had dedicated function keys representing the various logical elements of PLC programs.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Some proprietary programming terminals displayed the elements of PLC programs as graphic symbols, but plain ASCII character representations of contacts, coils, and wires were common.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Programs were stored on cassette tape cartridges.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Facilities for printing and documentation were minimal due to a lack of memory capacity.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] The oldest PLCs used magnetic-core memory.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] A PLC is an industrial microprocessor-based controller with programmable memory used to store program instructions and various functions.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs require a programming device that is used to develop and later download the created program into the memory of the controller.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Modern PLCs generally contain a real-time operating system, such as OS-9 or VxWorks.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] There are two types of mechanical design for PLC systems.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] A *single box* (also called a *brick*) is a small programmable controller that fits all units and interfaces into one compact casing, although, typically, additional expansion modules for inputs and outputs are available.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] The second design type – a *modular* PLC – has a chassis (also called a *rack*) that provides space for modules with different functions, such as power supply, processor, selection of I/O modules and communication interfaces – which all can be customized for the particular application.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Several racks can be administered by a single processor and may have thousands of inputs and outputs.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Either a special high-speed serial I/O link or comparable communication method is used so that racks can be distributed away from the processor, reducing the wiring costs for large plants.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Discrete (digital) signals can only take *on* or *off* value (1 or 0, *true* or *false*).
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Examples of devices providing a discrete signal include limit switches and photoelectric sensors.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Analog signals can use voltage or current that is analogous to the monitored variable and can take any value within their scale.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Pressure, temperature, flow, and weight are often represented by analog signals.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] These are typically interpreted as integer values with various ranges of accuracy depending on the device and the number of bits available to store the data.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] For example, an analog 0 to 10 V or 4-20 mA current loop input would be converted into an integer value of 0 to 32,767.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] The PLC will take this value and translate it into the desired units of the process so the operator or program can read it.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Some special processes need to work permanently with minimum unwanted downtime.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Therefore, it is necessary to design a system that is fault tolerant.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] In such cases, to increase the system availability in the event of hardware component failure, redundant CPU or I/O modules with the same functionality can be added to a hardware configuration to prevent a total or partial process shutdown due to hardware failure.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Other redundancy scenarios could be related to safety-critical processes, for example, large hydraulic presses could require that two PLCs turn on an output before the press can come down in case one PLC does not behave properly.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Programmable logic controllers are intended to be used by engineers without a programming background.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] For this reason, a graphical programming language called ladder logic was first developed.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] It resembles the schematic diagram of a system built with electromechanical relays and was adopted by many manufacturers and later standardized in the IEC 61131-3 control systems programming standard.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] As of 2015, it is still widely used, thanks to its simplicity.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] As of 2015, the majority of PLC systems adhere to the IEC 61131-3 standard that defines two textual programming languages: Structured Text (similar to Pascal) and Instruction List; as well as three graphical languages: ladder logic, function block diagram and sequential function chart.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Instruction List was deprecated in the third edition of the standard.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Modern PLCs can be programmed in a variety of ways, from the relay-derived ladder logic to programming languages such as specially adapted dialects of BASIC and C.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] While the fundamental concepts of PLC programming are common to all manufacturers, differences in I/O addressing, memory organization, and instruction sets mean that PLC programs are never perfectly interchangeable between different makers.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Even within the same product line of a single manufacturer, different models may not be directly compatible.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Manufacturers develop programming software for their PLCs.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] In addition to being able to program PLCs in multiple languages, they provide common features like hardware diagnostics and maintenance, software debugging, and offline simulation.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] PLC programs are typically written in a programming device, which can take the form of a desktop console, special software on a personal computer, or a handheld device.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] The program is then downloaded to the PLC through a cable connection or over a network.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] It is stored either in non-volatile flash memory or battery-backed-up RAM on the PLC.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] In some PLCs, the program is transferred from the programming device using a programming board that writes the program into a removable chip, such as EPROM, that is then inserted into the PLC.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] An incorrectly programmed PLC can result in lost productivity and dangerous conditions for programmed equipment.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] PLC simulation is a feature often found in PLC programming software.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] It allows for testing and debugging early in a project's development.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Testing the project in simulation improves its quality, increases the level of safety associated with equipment and can save time during the installation and commissioning of automated control applications since many scenarios can be tried and tested before the system is activated.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] The main difference compared to most other computing devices is that PLCs are intended for and therefore tolerant of more severe environmental conditions (such as dust, moisture, heat, cold), while offering extensive input/output (I/O) to connect the PLC to sensors and actuators.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] PLC input can include simple digital elements such as limit switches, analog variables from process sensors (such as temperature and pressure), and more complex data such as that from positioning or machine vision systems.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] PLC output can include elements such as indicator lamps, sirens, electric motors, pneumatic or hydraulic cylinders, magnetic relays, solenoids, or analog outputs.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] The input/output arrangements may be built into a simple PLC, or the PLC may have external I/O modules attached to a fieldbus or computer network that plugs into the PLC.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] The functionality of the PLC has evolved over the years to include sequential relay control, motion control, process control, distributed control systems, and networking.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] The data handling, storage, processing power, and communication capabilities of some modern PLCs are approximately equivalent to desktop computers.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] PLC-like programming combined with remote I/O hardware allows a general-purpose desktop computer to serve as a PLC in certain applications.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] The most basic function of a programmable logic controller is to emulate the functions of electromechanical relays.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Within the PLC programming environment, discrete inputs are given a unique address, and a PLC instruction can test if the input state is on or off.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Just as a series of relay contacts performs a logical AND function, not allowing current to pass unless all the contacts are closed, so a series of *examine if on* instructions will energize its output storage bit if all the input bits are on.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Similarly, a parallel set of instructions will perform a logical OR.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] In an electromechanical relay wiring diagram, a group of contacts controlling one coil is called a *rung* of a *ladder diagram*, and this concept is also used to describe PLC logic.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] The output of each rung sets or clears a storage bit, which may be associated with a discrete output or which may be an *internal coil* with no physical connection.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Such internal coils can be used, for example, as a common element in multiple separate rungs.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] More advanced instructions of the PLC may be implemented as functional blocks, which carry out some operation, such as manipulating an internal variable, when enabled by a logical input and which produce outputs to signal, for example, completion or errors.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs use built-in ports, such as USB, Ethernet, RS-232, RS-485, or RS-422 to communicate with external devices (sensors, actuators) and systems (programming tools, SCADA and other user interfaces).
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Communication is carried over various industrial network protocols, like Modbus, or EtherNet/IP.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Many of these protocols are vendor specific.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Formerly, some manufacturers offered dedicated communication modules as an add-on function where the processor had no network connection built in.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs used in larger I/O systems may have peer-to-peer (P2P) communication between processors.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] This allows separate parts of a complex process to have individual control while allowing the subsystems to coordinate over the communication link.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs may need to interact with people for the purpose of configuration, alarm reporting, or everyday control.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] A human-machine interface (HMI) is employed for this purpose.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] HMIs are also referred to as man-machine interfaces (MMIs) and graphical user interfaces (GUIs).
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] A simple system may use buttons and lights to interact with the user.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Text displays are available as well as graphical touch screens.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] More complex systems use programming and monitoring software installed on a computer, with the PLC connected via a communication interface.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] A PLC works in a program scan cycle, where it executes its program repeatedly.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] The program follows the sequence of instructions.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] It typically takes a time span of tens of milliseconds for the processor to evaluate all the instructions and update the status of all outputs.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] If the system contains remote I/O—for example, an external rack with I/O modules—then that introduces additional uncertainty in the response time of the PLC system.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Special-purpose I/O modules may be used where the scan time of the PLC is too long to allow predictable performance.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Precision timing modules, or counter modules for use with shaft encoders, are used where the scan time would be too long to reliably count pulses or detect the sense of rotation of an encoder.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] This allows even a relatively slow PLC to still interpret the counted values to control a machine, as the accumulation of pulses is done by a dedicated module that is unaffected by the speed of program execution.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] As PLCs became more advanced, methods were developed to change the sequence of ladder execution, and subroutines were implemented.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Prior to the discovery of the Stuxnet computer worm in June 2010, the security of PLCs received little attention.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Modern programmable controllers generally contain real-time operating systems, which can be vulnerable to exploits in a similar way as desktop operating systems.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs can also be attacked by gaining control of a computer they communicate with.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Since 2011, these concerns have grown as networking is becoming more commonplace in the PLC environment, connecting the previously separated plant floor networks and office networks.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] In February 2021, Rockwell Automation publicly disclosed a critical vulnerability affecting its Logix controller family.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] The secret cryptographic key used to verify communication between the PLC and workstation could be extracted from the programming software (Studio 5000 Logix Designer) and used to remotely change program code and configuration of a connected controller.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] The vulnerability was given a severity score of 10 out of 10 on the Common Vulnerability Scoring System.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Safety PLCs can be either a standalone device or safety-rated hardware and functionality added to existing controller architectures (Allen-Bradley GuardLogix, Siemens F-series, etc.).
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] These differ from conventional PLC types by being suitable for safety-critical applications for which PLCs have traditionally been supplemented with hard-wired safety relays and areas of the memory dedicated to the safety instructions.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] The standard of safety level is the safety integrity level (SIL).
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] A safety PLC might be used to control access to a robot cell with trapped-key access, or to manage the shutdown response to an emergency stop button on a conveyor production line.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Such PLCs typically have a restricted regular instruction set augmented with safety-specific instructions designed to interface with emergency stop buttons, light screens, and other safety-related devices.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs are well adapted to a range of automation tasks.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] These are typically industrial processes in manufacturing where the cost of developing and maintaining the automation system is high relative to the total cost of the automation system, and where changes to the system would be expected during its operational life.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] PLCs contain input and output devices compatible with industrial devices and controls; little electrical design is required, and the design problem centers on expressing the desired sequence of operations.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] PLC applications are typically highly customized systems, so the cost of a packaged PLC is low compared to the cost of a specific custom-built controller design.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] On the other hand, in the case of mass-produced goods, customized control systems are economical.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] This is due to the lower cost of the components, which can be optimally chosen instead of a *generic* solution, and where the non-recurring engineering charges are spread over thousands or millions of units.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] These are for small machines and systems with low or medium volume.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] They can execute PLC languages such as ladder logic, function block diagram and sequential function chart.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] They are similar to traditional PLCs, but their small size allows developers to design them into custom printed circuit boards like a microcontroller, without computer programming knowledge, but with a language that is easy to use, modify and maintain.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Architecturally, they sit between the classic PLC or micro-PLC and microcontrollers.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Automotive applications are an example; millions of units are built each year, and very few end-users alter the programming of these controllers.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] However, some specialty vehicles, such as transit buses, economically use PLCs instead of custom-designed controllers, because the volumes are low and the development cost would be uneconomical.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Very complex process control, such as that used in the chemical industry, may require algorithms and performance beyond the capability of even high-performance PLCs.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Very high-speed or precision controls may also require customized solutions; for example, aircraft flight controls.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Single-board computers using semi-customized or fully proprietary hardware may be chosen for very demanding control applications where the high development and maintenance cost can be supported.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] **Soft PLCs** running on desktop-type computers can interface with industrial I/O hardware while executing programs within a version of commercial operating systems adapted for process control needs.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] The rising popularity of single-board computers has also had an influence on the development of PLCs.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Traditional PLCs are generally closed platforms, but some newer PLCs (e.g., groov EPIC from Opto 22, ctrlX from Bosch Rexroth, PFC200 from Wago, PLCnext from Phoenix Contact, and Revolution Pi from Kunbus) provide the features of traditional PLCs on an open platform.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] In more recent years, small products called programmable logic relays (PLRs) or smart relays have become more common and accepted.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] These are similar to PLCs and are used in light industries where only a few points of I/O are needed, and low cost is desired.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] These small devices are typically made in a common physical size and shape by several manufacturers and branded by the makers of larger PLCs to fill their low-end product range.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Most of these have 8 to 12 discrete inputs, 4 to 8 discrete outputs, and up to 2 analog inputs.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Most have an RS-232 or RS-485 port for connecting to a PC so that programmers can use user-friendly software for programming instead of the small LCD and push-button set for this purpose.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Unlike regular PLCs that are usually modular and greatly expandable, the PLRs are usually not modular or expandable, but their cost can be significantly lower than that a PLC, and they still offer robust design and deterministic execution of the logic.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] A variant of PLCs, used in remote locations, is the remote terminal unit or RTU.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] An RTU is typically a low power, ruggedized PLC whose key function is to manage the communications links between the site and the central control system (typically SCADA) or in some modern systems, "The Cloud".
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] Unlike factory automation using wired communication protocols such as Ethernet, communications links to remote sites are often radio-based and are less reliable.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] To account for the reduced reliability, RTU will buffer messages or switch to alternate communications paths.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] When buffering messages, the RTU will timestamp each message so that a full history of site events can be reconstructed.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] RTUs, being PLCs, have a wide range of I/O and are fully programmable, typically with languages from the IEC 61131-3 standard that is common to many PLCs, RTUs and DCSs.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] In remote locations, it is common to use an RTU as a gateway for a PLC, where the PLC is performing all site control and the RTU is managing communications, time-stamping events and monitoring ancillary equipment.
[src:mes-manufacturing/programmable-logic-controller] On sites with only a handful of I/O, the RTU may also be the site PLC and will perform both communications and control functions.
[src:mes-manufacturing/shop-floor] The **shop floor** is the production area, such as in a factory or another working space and is the floor where workers produce goods.
[src:mes-manufacturing/shop-floor] The term "shop floor" refers to the area of a factory where production takes place.
[src:mes-manufacturing/shop-floor] The shop floor excludes the area used or designated for administrative activities.
[src:mes-manufacturing/shop-floor] A shop steward is an employee of a company or organization who, as a labor union member and official, represents and defends the interests of their coworkers.
[src:mes-manufacturing/shop-floor] During the First World War, the Shop Stewards Movement brought together shop stewards from across the United Kingdom.
[src:mes-manufacturing/shop-floor] It began with the Clyde Workers Committee, Britain's first shop stewards committee, which organized in response to the imprisonment of three of their members in 1915.
[src:mes-manufacturing/shop-floor] Systems for managing the various components of the manufacturing process are known as shop floor control (SFC) systems.
[src:mes-manufacturing/shop-floor] Shop floor control is one of the functions of manufacturing control; it is the process of monitoring the production activities as they happen, such as when the product is being processed, assembled, inspected, etc.
[src:mes-manufacturing/shop-floor] It is also concerned with the shop floor inventories—short and excessive inventories that may cause losses.
[src:mes-manufacturing/shop-floor] The manufacturing industry is significantly impacted by technological advances such as the Internet, the Web, and intelligent agents.
[src:mes-manufacturing/shop-floor] Changing shop floor environments and customer needs are sufficed with new kinds of shop floor control systems that are web-based shop floor control systems, also called e-shop floor or i-shop floor.
